## The Clwydian Range: A Geologic Sigh in North Wales

For those seeking designated tranquility, consult the [Clwydian Range AONB](/Clwydian_Range_AONB). For other iterations of "Clwyd," one might find clarity, or perhaps further confusion, at [Clwyd (disambiguation)](/Clwyd_(disambiguation)).

**Clwydian Range: The Clwydian Hills**

![Northern section of the Clwydian Range towards Liverpool Bay](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Clwydian_Range_towards_Liverpool_Bay.jpg/300px-Clwydian_Range_towards_Liverpool_Bay.jpg)
*The northern section of the Clwydian Range, gazing out towards the rather unremarkable expanse of [Liverpool Bay](/Liverpool_Bay).*

**Highest Point:** [Moel Famau](/Moel_Famau)
**Elevation:** A respectable, if not awe-inspiring, 554 meters (1,818 feet) above sea level.
**Coordinates:** 53°09′16″N 3°15′22″W﻿ / ﻿53.1544°N 3.25602°W﻿ / 53.1544; -3.25602. Should you feel the inexplicable urge to pinpoint its exact location.
**Dimensions:** A modest stretch of approximately 20 miles (32 km) in length, with a width that rarely exceeds 4 miles (6.4 km). Not exactly sprawling, is it?
**Naming:**
*   **Nickname:** Affectionately, or perhaps dismissively, known as the "Clwyds."
*   **Native Name:** *Bryniau Clwyd* in [Welsh](/Welsh_language), for those who appreciate linguistic heritage.

**Geography:**
*   **Location:** Firmly situated within [Wales](/Wales), a constituent country of [Great Britain](/Great_Britain).
*   **Region:** Specifically, it forms a prominent feature of [North Wales](/North_Wales).

**Geology:**
*   **Formation:** An upstanding block, meticulously sculpted from deep-sea [sediments](/Sediment).
*   **Rock Age:** These foundational rocks date back approximately 443.8 million years ago, a span of time that truly puts human concerns into perspective.
*   **Rock Type:** Predominantly [debris slurries](/Turbidite), patiently laid down during the [Silurian period](/Silurian). One might almost call it a slow, deliberate act of geological art.

The [Clwydian Range](/Clwydian_Range) (in [Welsh](/Welsh_language): *Bryniau Clwyd*), often referred to with a certain casualness as the Clwydian Hills or simply the Clwyds, represents a significant, though perhaps not overtly dramatic, series of [hills](/Hill) gracing the [north-east](/North-east_Wales) of [Wales](/Wales). This geological feature stretches its unassuming length from the southern reaches near [Llandegla](/Llandegla) all the way northwards to the coastal town of [Prestatyn](/Prestatyn). Its highest point, the rather aptly named [Moel Famau](/Moel_Famau), reaches a peak [elevation](/Summit) of 554 meters (1,818 feet). This entire range doesn't just exist; it forms the north-western, and arguably most defining, segment of the more expansive [Clwydian Range and Dee Valley](/Clwydian_Range_and_Dee_Valley) [Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty](/Area_of_Outstanding_Natural_Beauty). One might even say it's the poster child for the region, if hills had such aspirations.

### Geology

The summit of [Moel Famau](/Moel_Famau) is, rather predictably, strewn with remnants of its ancient past, specifically [Turbidite](/Turbidite).

The very fabric of the Clwydian Hills is constructed from an upstanding block of ancient [deep sea](/Deep_sea) [sediments](/Sediment), a testament to processes that unfolded with a glacial pace during the [Silurian](/Silurian) period. These sediments weren't just gently deposited; they were formed as vigorous [debris slurries](/Turbidite), originating from the then-nearby continental shelf and tumbling into the abyssal depths. It's a rather mundane origin story for something so prominent today.

The geological narrative continues with the older [mudstones](/Mudstone) and [siltstones](/Siltstone) of the Nantglyn Flags Formation, which now expose themselves along parts of the range's west-facing scarp slope. Overlying this ancient foundation is the Elwy Formation, a composition primarily of mudstones and siltstones, also deposited in deep marine conditions, but notably interspersed with numerous [sandstone](/Sandstone) beds. This Elwy Formation constitutes the bulk of the higher ground, giving the hills their current profile. Both of these formations, the Nantglyn Flags and the Elwy, are dated to the [Ludlovian](/Ludlow_epoch) age, a specific epoch within the Silurian period, roughly 427 to 420 million years ago.

The rocks of the Clwydian Range are, to put it mildly, intensely [faulted](/Fault_(geology)). It's almost as if the Earth itself couldn't decide on a single direction. The most significant of these geological ruptures is the Vale of Clwyd Fault, a colossal structural discontinuity that is directly responsible for the impressive, almost theatrical, west-facing [scarp](/Escarpment) of the Clwydian Range. This fault has effectively downthrown the younger [Carboniferous](/Carboniferous) and [Permo-Triassic](/Permian) rocks to the west, creating a stark geological boundary that separates the distinct formations of the [Vale of Clwyd](/Vale_of_Clwyd) from the older, more resilient rocks of the hills themselves.

Further shaping this landscape, though much more recently in geological terms, was the movement of ice from the Welsh [ice-sheet](/Ice-sheet) during the [last ice age](/Last_Glacial_Period). This colossal sheet of ice advanced eastwards, inexorably pushing over the Clwydian Hills and even interacting with the larger Irish Sea Ice to the east of the range. The legacy of this icy behemoth is still visible in the form of numerous glacial [meltwater channels](/Meltwater_channel) scattered around the range. Furthermore, the valley carved by the [River Wheeler](/River_Wheeler), which rather inconveniently cuts the range in two, served as a particularly significant drainage channel for these massive meltwaters. Apparently, even ancient ice had its preferred routes.

### Geography

The elevated positions within the Clwydian Range afford rather extensive, if somewhat predictable, views. To the west, one can observe the distant, more dramatic peaks of [Snowdonia](/Snowdonia). Eastwards, the gaze sweeps across the sprawling, relatively flat expanse of the [Cheshire Plain](/Cheshire_Plain) towards the distant, industrial hum of the [Peak District](/Peak_District). Further to the northeast, the urban sprawls of [Manchester](/Manchester) and [Liverpool](/Liverpool) in England make their presence known, a stark contrast to the natural beauty. For those inclined to prolonged perambulation, the [Offa's Dyke National Trail](/Offa%27s_Dyke_Path) conveniently traverses the range's high ground, guiding walkers from [Llandegla](/Llandegla) in the south to [Prestatyn](/Prestatyn) on the coast.

![Moel Arthur from Moel Llys-y-Coed](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Moel_Arthur_from_Moel_Llys-y-Coed.jpg/300px-Moel_Arthur_from_Moel_Llys-y-Coed.jpg)
*[Moel Arthur](/Moel_Arthur) observed from the slightly higher vantage point of Moel Llys-y-Coed. One hill, looking at another. Riveting.*

These hills, predominantly characterized by their heather-clad uplands that gradually transition into verdant pastures, are not merely geological formations. They are also historical repositories, boasting no fewer than six well-preserved [Iron Age](/Iron_Age) [hillforts](/Hillfort). These ancient defensive structures include Y Foel (also known as [Moel Hiraddug](/Moel_Hiraddug)), [Moel-y-gaer](/Moel_y_Gaer,_Bodfari), [Penycloddiau](/Penycloddiau), [Moel Arthur](/Moel_Arthur), a second [Moel y Gaer](/Moel_y_Gaer,_Llanbedr), and [Foel Fenlli](/Foel_Fenlli). One can only imagine the ancient inhabitants, huddled atop these strategic positions, gazing out at the same views, albeit with far more pressing concerns than panoramic photography. Beyond these imposing fortifications, the hills are also dotted with numerous [tumuli](/Tumuli) and [cairns](/Cairn), silent monuments to long-forgotten burials and rituals, adding a layer of archaeological intrigue to the natural landscape. Humanity, always leaving its mark, even when it thinks it's just admiring a view.

